   },
   "source": [
    "## Exploratory Analysis and Regression - Automobile Data\n",
    "\n",
    "### About the data set\n",
    "\n",
    "This data set is from the [Univerisity of California Irvine Machine Learning Repository](https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Automobile)  The data was compiled by Jeffrey C. Schlimmer from the following sources:\n",
    "\n",
    "- 1985 Model Import Car and Truck Specifications, 1985 Ward's Automotive Yearbook. \n",
    "- Personal Auto Manuals, Insurance Services Office, 160 Water Street, New York, NY 10038 \n",
    "- Insurance Collision Report, Insurance Institute for Highway Safety, Watergate 600, Washington, DC 20037\n",
    "\n",
    "This data set consists of three types of entities: \n",
    "- (a) The specification of an auto in terms of various characteristics \n",
    "- (b) Tts assigned insurance risk rating. This corresponds to the degree to which the auto is more risky than its price indicates. Cars are initially assigned a risk factor symbol associated with its price. Then, if it is more risky (or less), this symbol is adjusted by moving it up (or down) the scale. Actuaries call this process \"symboling\".\n",
    "- (c) Its normalized losses in use as compared to other cars. This is the relative average loss payment per insured vehicle year. This value is normalized for all autos within a particular size classification (two-door small, station wagons, sports/speciality, etc...), and represents the average loss per car per year. \n",
    "\n",
    "### Objective\n",
    "\n",
    "The aim here is to explore the data set and find basic relationships of different features with an automobile's price. We will be starting with some brief exploratory analysis involving summary statistics and graphical visualization. We will also be conducting a few tests of hypotheses on the study variable `price`. We also want to see if there is a way to predict the price of the automobiles given all the information we have. We will be comparing a few different regression models to find the best one. \n",
    "\n",
    "### Load and examine the data set\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's get started. The function shown in the cell below loads the data from the .csv file. Some minimal clean up is performed on the data. Rows with missing values are dropped and some columns are converted from strings containing numbers to numeric data."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {
    "_cell_guid": "18a31e16-e737-4ec5-9b9f-e18e6a931d95",
    "_uuid": "68b21673b20ce542405d452fcf969c783303f9df"
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Warning message in lapply(auto.price[, numcols], as.numeric):\n",
      "“NAs introduced by coercion”Warning message in lapply(auto.price[, numcols], as.numeric):\n",
      "“NAs introduced by coercion”Warning message in lapply(auto.price[, numcols], as.numeric):\n",
      "“NAs introduced by coercion”Warning message in lapply(auto.price[, numcols], as.numeric):\n",
      "“NAs introduced by coercion”Warning message in lapply(auto.price[, numcols], as.numeric):\n",
      "“NAs introduced by coercion”"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "read.auto <- function(file = '../input/Automobile_data.csv')\n",
    "{\n",
    "  ## Read the csv file\n",
    "  auto.price <- read.csv(file, header = TRUE, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)\n",
    "\n",
    "  ## Coerce some character columns to numeric\n",
    "  numcols <- c('price', 'bore', 'stroke', 'horsepower', 'peak.rpm')\n",
    "  auto.price[, numcols] <- lapply(auto.price[, numcols], as.numeric)\n",
    "\n",
    "  ## Remove cases or rows with missing values. In this case we keep the rows which do not have NAs. \n",
    "  auto.price[complete.cases(auto.price), ]\n",
    "}\n",
    "auto.data <- read.auto()"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "### Summary statistics\n",
    "\n",
    "We can learn a lot about a data set by looking at statistical summaries. The most common ones are Mean & Standard Deviation. The mean is a measure of central tendency and is defined as:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$mean = \\mu = \\frac{1}{n} \\Sigma_i x_i$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The standard deviation is a measure of the dispersion of a distribution defined as:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$sd = \\sigma = sqrt(\\frac{1}{1-n} \\Sigma_i (\\mu - x_i)^2$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's look at the summaries for the numeric attributes of the data set below:"
   ]

   "source": [
    "Note that the upper interquartile ranges are different from the lower IQR, indicating the distributions are skewed. The mean and the median are also quite different. Again this is a sign of a skewed distribution. \n",
    "\n",
    "### Frequency tables\n",
    "\n",
    "The summary techniques we have used so far are suitable only for numeric variables. Categorical variables have values which are typically unordered. Therefore, we need a method to summarize categorical variables based on counts. Frequency tabulation is one way of getting a better idea of the distribution of categorical variables."
   ]

   "source": [
    "Notice that there are more Standard cars than there are Turbo & that most are Gasoline!\n",
    "\n",
    "### Covariance and correlation\n",
    "\n",
    "Covariance is a measure of how much two random variables change together.  Covariance is defined as follows:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$cov(x,y) = E((x - \\mu_x) (y - \\mu_y))$$\n",
    "\n",
    "If the greater values of one variable mainly correspond with the greater values of the other variable, and the same holds for the lesser values, i.e., the variables tend to show similar behavior, the covariance is positive. In the opposite case, when the greater values of one variable mainly correspond to the lesser values of the other, i.e., the variables tend to show opposite behavior, the covariance is negative. The sign of the covariance therefore shows the tendency in the linear relationship between the variables. The magnitude of the covariance is not easy to interpret because it is not normalized. The normalized version of the covariance is called the correlation coefficient.\n",
    "\n",
    "Pearson's correlation coefficient is similar to covariance, but with normalization by the variance, and is defined as follows: \n",
    "\n",
    "$$cor(x,y) = \\frac{E((x - \\mu_x) (y - \\mu_y))}{\\sigma_x \\sigma_y}$$"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "The correlation matrix is a bit easier to understand, since the values are normalized. The diagonal values of the correlation matrix are all 1.0, as a result of the normalization. The magnitudes of the correlation values between the variables range between -1.0 and +1.0. A magnitude closer to +1.0 or -1.0 indicates a high correlation.\n",
    "\n",
    "Some pairs of variables are weakly correlated, with small magnitudes. For example, **wheel base** and **horsepower** are weakly correlated, whereas **engine size** and **curb weight** are strongly correlated. \n",
    "\n",
    "### Data Visualization\n",
    "\n",
    "Here are some of the basic chart types used to visualize data:\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Bar plots**: Bar plots are used to display the counts or frequency of unique values of a categorical variable. The height of the bar represents the count for each unique category of the variable. \n",
    "- **Histograms**: Histograms are similar to bar plots, except that they are used for numeric variables\n",
    "- **Box plots**: Box plots, also known as box and whisker plots, were introduced by John Tukey in 1970. Box plots are another way to visualize the distribution of data values. In this respect, box plots are comparable to histograms, but are quite different in presentation. \n",
    "- **Kernel Density Estimation Plots**:  Kernel density estimation uses a moving denisty kernel to average the density of the distribution. These are similar to Histogram, except that they show a smooth curve.\n",
    "- **Scatter plots**: A basic scatter plot shows the relationship between two variables. Points are ploted at the x-y coordinates of each value pair. Pair wise plots, also know as plot matrices, allow you to view multiple dimensions of a data set on one plot. A scatter plot is shown of each variable versus all other variables, arranged in an array\n",
    "- **Line plots**: Line plots are used to show the relationship between variables with ordered values. \n",
    "- **Correlation plots**: The correlation structure of a multivariate data set can provide some useful insight. However, it is hard to derive much insight by just looking at the matrix of numbers. A visualization can be useful in getting an overall impression of which variables have siginificant correlation. \n",
    "\n",
    "Next, let's look at some basic plots"
   ]

   "source": [
    "require(ellipse)\n",
    "#Correlation Plot\n",
    "plotcorr(R, col = colorRampPalette(c(\"firebrick3\", \"white\", \"navy\"))(10))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "_cell_guid": "bc2b1dc1-ce34-4fbb-b08b-ffa7c0f298fd",
    "_uuid": "01a2b49cf7b33a5744228387289fb2b73efd2685"
   },
   "source": [
    "In the above plot, the length of the minor axis is computed as $1 - correlation$. A correlation of 1 gives a line, with the \n",
    "minor axis set to 0. Correlation of zero results in a circle. The intensity of the color used on the plot indicates the \n",
    "magnitude of the correlation. Additionally, orientation of the ellipse is used to highlight the positive or negative correlation\n",
    "value. For positive correlation the ellipse tilts right, with the opposite being true for negative correlation.\n",
    "\n",
    "Next, let's see some examples of scatter plots below"
   ]

   "source": [
    "#Scatter Plots\n",
    "require(ggplot2)\n",
    "require(gridExtra)\n",
    "Plot1 <- ggplot(auto.sub, aes(x = price, y = horsepower)) + geom_point() + \n",
    "    xlab('Price') + ylab('Horsepower') + \n",
    "    ggtitle('Relationship btwn Price & Horsepower') +\n",
    "    theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 6.5, face = \"bold\"))\n",
    "Plot2 <- ggplot(auto.sub, aes(x = price, y = wheel.base)) + geom_point() + \n",
    "    xlab('Price') + ylab('Wheel Base') + \n",
    "    ggtitle('Relationship btwn Price & Wheel Base')+\n",
    "    theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 6.5, face = \"bold\"))\n",
    "Plot3 <- ggplot(auto.sub, aes(x = price, y = length)) + geom_point() + \n",
    "    xlab('Price') + ylab('Length') + \n",
    "    ggtitle('Relationship btwn Price & Car Length')+\n",
    "    theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 6.5, face = \"bold\"))\n",
    "Plot4 <- ggplot(auto.sub, aes(x = price, y = width)) + geom_point() + \n",
    "    xlab('Price') + ylab('Width') + \n",
    "    ggtitle('Relationship btwn Price & Car Width') +\n",
    "    theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 6.5, face = \"bold\"))\n",
    "Plot5 <- ggplot(auto.sub, aes(x = price, y = height)) + geom_point() + \n",
    "    xlab('Price') + ylab('Height') + \n",
    "    ggtitle('Relationship btwn Price & Car Height') +\n",
    "    theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 6.5, face = \"bold\"))\n",
    "Plot6 <- ggplot(auto.sub, aes(x = price, y = curb.weight)) + geom_point() + \n",
    "    xlab('Price') + ylab('curb.weight') + \n",
    "    ggtitle('Relationship btwn Price & curb.weight') +\n",
    "    theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 6.5, face = \"bold\"))\n",
    "Plot7 <- ggplot(auto.sub, aes(x = price, y = engine.size)) + geom_point() + \n",
    "    xlab('Price') + ylab('engine.size') + \n",
    "    ggtitle('Relationship btwn Price & engine.size') +\n",
    "    theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 6.5, face = \"bold\"))\n",
    "Plot8 <- ggplot(auto.sub, aes(x = price, y = bore)) + geom_point() + \n",
    "    xlab('Price') + ylab('bore') + \n",
    "    ggtitle('Relationship btwn Price & bore') +\n",
    "    theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 6.5, face = \"bold\"))\n",
    "Plot9 <- ggplot(auto.sub, aes(x = price, y = stroke)) + geom_point() + \n",
    "    xlab('Price') + ylab('stroke') + \n",
    "    ggtitle('Relationship btwn Price & stroke') +\n",
    "    theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 6.5, face = \"bold\"))\n",
    "Plot10 <- ggplot(auto.sub, aes(x = price, y = compression.ratio)) + geom_point() + \n",
    "    xlab('Price') + ylab('compression.ratio') + \n",
    "    ggtitle('Relationship btwn Price & compression.ratio') +\n",
    "    theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 6.5, face = \"bold\"))\n",
    "Plot11 <- ggplot(auto.sub, aes(x = price, y = peak.rpm)) + geom_point() + \n",
    "    xlab('Price') + ylab('peak.rpm') + \n",
    "    ggtitle('Relationship btwn Price & peak.rpm') +\n",
    "    theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 6.5, face = \"bold\"))\n",
    "Plot12 <- ggplot(auto.sub, aes(x = price, y = city.mpg)) + geom_point() + \n",
    "    xlab('Price') + ylab('city.mpg') + \n",
    "    ggtitle('Relationship btwn Price & city.mpg') +\n",
    "    theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 6.5, face = \"bold\"))\n",
    "Plot13 <- ggplot(auto.sub, aes(x = price, y = highway.mpg)) + geom_point() + \n",
    "    xlab('Price') + ylab('highway.mpg') + \n",
    "    ggtitle('Relationship between Price and highway.mpg')\n",
    "\n",
    "grid.arrange(Plot1, Plot2, Plot3, Plot4, Plot5, Plot6, Plot7, Plot8, Plot9, Plot10, Plot11, Plot12, ncol = 3)\n",
    "Plot13"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "Below, we look at the relationship of automobile **`price`** with other numeric variables**\n",
    "\n",
    "The pair wise scatter plot matrix below contains a number of elements, which are useful for understanding the relationships in the data sets. \n",
    "\n",
    "- There are Kernel Density Estimation plots for each variable along the diagonal of the matrix. \n",
    "- A pair of scatter plots for each variable pair is displayed. These two scatter plots show the axes in both possible orientations.\n",
    "- A linear regression line is shown in green on each scatter plot. This regression line gives an indiction of trend.\n",
    "- A nonlinear regression line with confidence intervals is shown in solid red. The nonlinear regression line can highlight more complex relationships in the data set. The confidence intervals, shown as dotted red lines, give some indication of the likely range of regression lines, given the uncertainty in the data.  \n",
    "\n",
    "**Note**: We will be addressing regression shortly"
   ]

   "source": [
    "require(car)\n",
    "require(repr)\n",
    "options(repr.plot.width=9, repr.plot.height=9)\n",
    "scatterplotMatrix(~ wheel.base + horsepower + length + width + price, data = auto.sub)\n",
    "scatterplotMatrix(~ height + curb.weight + engine.size + bore + price, data = auto.sub)\n",
    "scatterplotMatrix(~ stroke + compression.ratio + peak.rpm + city.mpg + highway.mpg + price, data = auto.sub)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "_cell_guid": "ada4e16f-0c98-4a6f-875a-b11d7817aadf",
    "_uuid": "ee9e1aa3abeff960ee4a2289364822004abf98bc"
   },
   "source": [
    "Now that we have done some basic exploration and visualization of our data, let's proceed with some exploratory tests of hypotheses. We will test the following:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Test if **`price`** or **`log(price)`** follows normal distribution\n",
    "\n",
    "2. Test for significance of price/log(price) stratified by:\n",
    " \n",
    " a. Fuel type (diesel Vs gas)\n",
    " \n",
    " b. Aspiration (Turbo Vs Standard)\n",
    " \n",
    "3. Apply ANOVA & Tukey's HSD to compare the price (log(price)) of autos stratified by Body Style\n",
    "\n",
    "### Hypothesis Tests\n",
    "\n",
    "A statistical **hypothesis**, sometimes called confirmatory data analysis, is a hypothesis that is testable on the basis of observing a process that is modeled via a set of random variables. A statistical hypothesis test is a method of statistical inference. Commonly, two statistical data sets are compared, or a data set obtained by sampling is compared against a synthetic data set from an idealized model. A hypothesis is proposed for the statistical relationship between the two data sets, and this is compared as an **alternative** to an idealized **null hypothesis** that proposes no relationship between two data sets. The comparison is deemed statistically significant if the relationship between the data sets would be an unlikely realization of the null hypothesis according to a threshold probability—the significance level. Hypothesis tests are used in determining what outcomes of a study would lead to a rejection of the null hypothesis for a pre-specified level of significance.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Hypothesis testing steps\n",
    "\n",
    "Brief description of the steps involved:\n",
    "\n",
    "- We first state our population assumptions in the null hypothesis: $H_0$.\n",
    "- We state a new hypothesis as an alternative to the null: $H_a$.\n",
    "- The null + alternative should make up all possible outcomes and be mutually exclusive.\n",
    "- Decide on a significance level (probability cutoff): 0.90, 0.95, and 0.99 are common (problem specific).\n",
    "\n",
    "Based on our findings we can only do two things\n",
    "- **Reject the null-hypothesis:** Since the alternative covers all other possibilities, we can say we accept the alternative hypothesis.\n",
    "- **Fail to reject the null hypothesis:**  We accept the null hypothesis because we have already believed our null hypothesis from the start. \n",
    "\n",
    "### What is  the p-value?\n",
    "\n",
    "Results of hypothesis tests are often reported as a p-value.  \n",
    "\n",
    "- In technical terms, a p-value is the probability of obtaining an effect **at least as extreme** as the one in your sample data, assuming the null hypothesis is true. A hig p-value implies we cannot reject the null hypothesis.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Testing distributions\n",
    "\n",
    "Test statistics, and other statistics, often make distribution assumptions. This raises the question: how can we test a distribution assumption?\n",
    "\n",
    "We can test this graphically using Q-Q plots and by using numerical tests like Kolmogorov-Smirnov test for distributions. Let's explore below:"
   ]

   "source": [
    "#Q1: Compare & test normality of the distribution of price & log(price). Use both graphical method and a formal test\n",
    "\n",
    "sampleA <- auto.sub$price\n",
    "\n",
    "# random sample from normal distribution with  mean(price) and standard deviation = sd(price)\n",
    "m <- mean(sampleA)\n",
    "s <- sd(sampleA)\n",
    "cat(paste('Mean of auto price = ', as.character(round(m,2)),', variance = ', as.character(round(s^2,2)),', \n",
    "            standard deviation = ', as.character(round(s,2))))\n",
    "sampleB <- rnorm(195, mean = m, sd = s)\n",
    "\n",
    "sampleLogA <- log(auto.sub$price)\n",
    "\n",
    "# random sample from normal distribution with  mean(log(price)) and standard deviation = sd(log(price))\n",
    "lm <- mean(sampleLogA)\n",
    "ls <- sd(sampleLogA)\n",
    "cat(paste('\\nMean of logarithm of auto price = ', as.character(round(lm,2)),', variance = ', as.character(round(ls^2,2)),', \n",
    "         standard deviation = ', as.character(round(ls,2))))\n",
    "sampleNormB <- rnorm(195, mean = lm, sd = ls)\n",
    "\n",
    "#Plot the density curve of the price variable\n",
    "Plot1 <- ggplot(auto.sub, aes(price)) + geom_density()\n",
    "\n",
    "#Plot the density curve of the log(price) variable\n",
    "Plot2 <- ggplot(auto.sub, aes(log(price))) + geom_density()\n",
    "\n",
    "grid.arrange(Plot1, Plot2, ncol = 2)"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "#stacked plot of the histogram of price Vs normal distribution with mean = 13248.02,  and standard deviation = 8056.33 \n",
    "# for comparison purposes\n",
    "options(repr.plot.width=5, repr.plot.height=10)\n",
    "  par(mfrow=c(2,1))\n",
    "  {\n",
    "   hist(auto.sub$price, main=paste('Auto price Vs N(13248.02, 8056.33)'),  freq=FALSE, xlim = c(-10000,50000))\n",
    "   x_norm <- seq(-10000,50000, length = 195)#we're using length = 195 because we have 195 observations in the automobile data\n",
    "   y_norm <- dnorm(x_norm, mean = m,sd = s)\n",
    "   lines(x_norm, y_norm, xlim = c(-10000,50000))   \n",
    "  }\n",
    "  par(mfrow=c(1,1))\n",
    "  \n",
    "#Let's use stacked plots for comparison again with log(price) and random sample from N(9.35, 0.51)\n",
    "  par(mfrow=c(2,1))\n",
    "  {\n",
    "   hist(log(auto.sub$price), main=paste('Log(auto price) Vs N(9.35, 0.51)'), freq=FALSE, xlim = c(8,12))\n",
    "   x_norm <- seq(7.5,12, length = 195)\n",
    "   y_norm <- dnorm(x_norm, mean = lm,sd = ls)\n",
    "   lines(x_norm, y_norm, xlim = c(8,12))   \n",
    "   }\n",
    "   par(mfrow=c(1,1))"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "Here, we have plotted the histogram of price (figure above) & log(price) (figure below) againt respective normal distributions with mean and standard deviations of price & log(price) respectively. We see here that log(price) looks closer to having a normal distribution than just the price. Let's go a step further and check with Q-Q plots.\n",
    "\n",
    "###  Q-Q plot\n",
    "\n",
    "The qualtile-quantile (Q-Q) plot provides a handy visual means to inspect the Normality of a data set. If the sample is Normal the data points will fall in a straight line. "
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "options(repr.plot.width=8, repr.plot.height=4)\n",
    "\n",
    "par(mfrow=c(1,2))\n",
    "#Q-Q plot of price\n",
    "qqnorm(sampleA, main = 'Q-Q plot of price'); qqline(sampleA, col = 2)\n",
    "#Q-Q plot of log(price)\n",
    "qqnorm(sampleLogA, main = 'Q-Q plot of log(price)'); qqline(sampleLogA, col = 2)\n",
    "par(mfrow=c(1,1))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "_cell_guid": "321e43d0-114f-44de-be2d-db0caedec20a",
    "_uuid": "49016ab03ed35fa0d9bc7957f2ebbca482fa7635"
   },
   "source": [
    "Since the Q-Q plot on the left is clearly not a straight line, this (auto price) most likely does not follow a normal distribution.\n",
    "\n",
    "Although the plot on the right appears less curvier than the Q-Q plot to the left, it is still hard to say if log(auto price) most likely follows a normal distribution or not. Now let's go ahead an run a test to see what we get.\n",
    "\n",
    "### The Kolmogorov-Smirnov test for distributions\n",
    "\n",
    "The Kolmogorov-Smirnov test a general test of a distribution. The K-S statistic is just the maximum vertical distance between two CDFs. Since it is based on a simple deviation the K-S test can test departure from any hypothetical distribution, not just normal.\n",
    "\n",
    "Here, we are testing if **`price` ~ `N(mean(price), sd(price))`**"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "#calculate the cumulative distribution of price Vs random sample from N(13248.02, 8056.33)\n",
    "x_seq <- seq(-10000,40000,len=195)\n",
    "y_cdf1 <- sapply(x_seq, function(x){sum(sampleA<x)/195})#cdf of price\n",
    "y_cdf2 <- sapply(x_seq, function(x){sum(sampleB<x)/195})#cdf of normal distribution N(13248.02, 8056.33)\n",
    "\n",
    "#Kolmogorov-Smirnov test statistic\n",
    "k_s_stat <- max(abs(y_cdf1 - y_cdf2))\n",
    "cat(paste('Kolmogorov-Smirnov Statistic = ', as.character(k_s_stat)))\n",
    "\n",
    "options(repr.plot.width=8, repr.plot.height=4)\n",
    "par(mfrow=c(1,2))\n",
    "#Plot the cumulative distribution function of price Vs random sample from N(13248.02, 8056.33)\n",
    "plot(ecdf(sampleA), col='blue', main ='CDFs of samples', xlab = 'Value', ylab = 'Cumulative density')\n",
    "lines(ecdf(sampleB), col='red')\n",
    "\n",
    "#Where does the KS statistic occur on the graph?\n",
    "k_index <- which.max(abs(y_cdf1-y_cdf2))\n",
    "k_s_x <- x_seq[k_index]\n",
    "plot(x_seq,y_cdf1, col='blue', pch=16, main ='CDFs of samples',xlab = 'Value', ylab = 'Cumulative density')\n",
    "points(x_seq,y_cdf2,col='red', pch=16) \n",
    "lines(c(k_s_x,k_s_x), c(y_cdf1[k_index],y_cdf2[k_index]), col='black', lwd=8)\n",
    "par(mfrow=c(1,1))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "_cell_guid": "fca8a6f2-313c-4743-aa87-afa53cb8c2a4",
    "_uuid": "e5c785f845f2fb3a5fb5aa757c04f2051b94e27b"
   },
   "source": [
    "Now let's run the K-S test for the **price**\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Here we are testing:\n",
    "\n",
    "    Null hypothesis: **$H_0$**: `price` follows `N(mean(price), sd(price))` **Vs**\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Alternative hypothesis **$H_a$**: `price` does not follow `N(mean(price), sd(price))`\n",
    "\n",
    "At 95% confidence. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "metadata": {
    "_cell_guid": "5b9c7c1d-087e-4b7a-aa03-09b8654d4646",
    "_uuid": "9f89a7f431fdcc0ed77a93f204b175e4052861a5"
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Warning message in ks.test(sampleA, sampleB, alternative = \"two.sided\"):\n",
      "“p-value will be approximate in the presence of ties”"
     ]
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "\n",
       "\tTwo-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov test\n",
       "\n",
       "data:  sampleA and sampleB\n",
       "D = 0.16923, p-value = 0.00751\n",
       "alternative hypothesis: two-sided\n"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "ks.test(sampleA, sampleB, alternative = \"two.sided\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "_cell_guid": "1a496748-f636-444d-925a-360cb198b4d0",
    "_uuid": "e6e2c34cb98bb889929267d018c20da0bce05f01"
   },
   "source": [
    "Since p-value (chance that the price observations came from a N(13248.02, 8056.33) distribution) is  significantly < 0.05 we **reject the null hypothesis**. This means that we cannot say that the price observations came from a normal population\n",
    "\n",
    "Now, let's repeat these steps for the logarithm of price. Here we're testing if **`log(price)` ~ `N(mean(log(price)), sd(log(price)))`**"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "#Now let's calculate the same for the logarithm of price Vs random sample from N(9.35, 0.51)\n",
    "x_seq1 <- seq(8,11,len=100)\n",
    "y_cdfLog1 <- sapply(x_seq1, function(x){sum(sampleLogA<x)/195})\n",
    "y_cdfLog2 <- sapply(x_seq1, function(x){sum(sampleNormB<x)/195})\n",
    "\n",
    "#Kolmogorov-Smirnov test statistic\n",
    "k_s_stat1 <- max(abs(y_cdfLog1 - y_cdfLog2))\n",
    "cat(paste('Kolmogorov-Smirnov Statistic = ', as.character(k_s_stat1)))\n",
    "\n",
    "options(repr.plot.width=8, repr.plot.height=4)\n",
    "par(mfrow=c(1,2))\n",
    "#Plot the cumulative distribution function of price Vs random sample from N(9.35, 0.51)\n",
    "plot(ecdf(sampleLogA), col='blue', main ='CDFs of samples', xlab = 'Value', ylab = 'Cumulative density')\n",
    "lines(ecdf(sampleNormB), col='red')\n",
    "\n",
    "#Where does the KS statistic occur on the graph?\n",
    "k_index1 <- which.max(abs(y_cdfLog1 - y_cdfLog2))\n",
    "k_s_x1 <- x_seq1[k_index1]\n",
    "\n",
    "plot(x_seq1,y_cdfLog1, col='blue', pch=16, main ='CDFs of samples', xlab = 'Value', ylab = 'Cumulative density')\n",
    "points(x_seq1,y_cdfLog2,col='red', pch=16) \n",
    "lines(c(k_s_x1,k_s_x1), c(y_cdfLog1[k_index1],y_cdfLog2[k_index1]),col='black', lwd=8)\n",
    "par(mfrow=c(1,1))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "_cell_guid": "841c3750-6e58-4b9d-9036-dfb6e66539fb",
    "_uuid": "37d9838f9628633f38db59608f932e69f199715a"
   },
   "source": [
    "Let's run the K-S test for **log(price)**\n",
    "\n",
    "2. Here we are testing:\n",
    "\n",
    "    Null hypothesis: **$H_0$**: `log(price)` follows `N(mean(log(price)), sd(log(price)))` **Vs**\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Alternative hypothesis **$H_a$**: `log(price)` does not follow `N(mean(log(price)), sd(log(price)))`\n",
    "\n",
    "At 95% confidence. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "metadata": {
    "_cell_guid": "c4012524-9a54-45ba-9684-7a4fa1ae9e08",
    "_uuid": "27184bf0fa5fbd4abde9dba4e7454e38b046d13e"
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Warning message in ks.test(sampleLogA, sampleNormB, alternative = \"two.sided\"):\n",
      "“p-value will be approximate in the presence of ties”"
     ]
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "\n",
       "\tTwo-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov test\n",
       "\n",
       "data:  sampleLogA and sampleNormB\n",
       "D = 0.13333, p-value = 0.06244\n",
       "alternative hypothesis: two-sided\n"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "ks.test(sampleLogA, sampleNormB, alternative = \"two.sided\") "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "_cell_guid": "6cc62352-7643-48eb-b05f-a8bdf533a1d6",
    "_uuid": "64be1c5ec7669c62bee989a02d8d9ec4e76ace6e"
   },
   "source": [
    "Since p-value (chance that the natural logarithm of price observations came from a N(9.35, 0.51) distribution) > 0.05 we **cannot reject the null hypothesis**. This means that there is a likelihood that these observations came from a normal population\n",
    "\n",
    "The K-S test is rather general, as it can be applied to test any distribution. However, this means that the *power* of this test is limited. The *power* of a test is the probability of rejecting a null hypothesis when the alternative is true. There are ways to calculate the power of a test at any given level of significance and sample size, but we will not be delving into it here.\n",
    "\n",
    "A more powerful test can be created by adopting more restrictive assumptions. For example, the Shapiro-Wilk test has greater power, but is specifically for Normal distributions. Let's use the S-W test to determine if price or log(price) are normal:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "metadata": {
    "_cell_guid": "46058883-c9bb-4460-87f8-89340062aaa8",
    "_uuid": "36411f186a4e44a6d1d465403bfc5375dd3d2c32"
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "\n",
       "\tShapiro-Wilk normality test\n",
       "\n",
       "data:  sampleA\n",
       "W = 0.79939, p-value = 4.265e-15\n"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "shapiro.test(sampleA)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 19,
   "metadata": {
    "_cell_guid": "2bea60d1-f798-4280-8ed4-65dc90756e7c",
    "_uuid": "b4ef3afa5679921b91fdf34d9d8d17d4fd152912"
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "\n",
       "\tShapiro-Wilk normality test\n",
       "\n",
       "data:  sampleLogA\n",
       "W = 0.9464, p-value = 1.141e-06\n"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "shapiro.test(sampleLogA)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "_cell_guid": "6506343a-1b53-43b0-b9e5-3cbdd8b5025f",
    "_uuid": "b5a932e5b587d0bae66a8206827d1437cf7b2649"
   },
   "source": [
    "In both cases [price and log(price)], we can say that **neither observations are from a normal population** since p-value is significantly < 0.05\n",
    "\n",
    "In summary, we could not find evidence that the price follows a nomal distribution, but log(price) may have come from a normal population based on the Q-Q plots & KS test.\n",
    "\n",
    "Since log(price) more or less follows a normal distribution, we will use this for further analysis"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 20,
   "metadata": {
    "_cell_guid": "0b76559f-2b66-451e-8244-bb2f4abca9eb",
    "_uuid": "39ca045d777b16397ce091192ab0e3bff72dc0df"
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "\n",
       "diesel    gas \n",
       "    20    175 "
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "\n",
       "  std turbo \n",
       "  159    36 "
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "#Q2: Test significance of log(price) stratified by:\n",
    "#a. Fuel type\n",
    "#b. Aspiration\n",
    "#Use both graphical methods & a formal test\n",
    "\n",
    "#Let's split the price vector by Fuel Type\n",
    "table(auto.sub$fuel.type)\n",
    "priceFType <- split(auto.sub$price, as.factor(auto.sub$fuel.type), drop = FALSE)\n",
    "\n",
    "#Compute logarithms\n",
    "logPriceGas <- log(priceFType$gas)\n",
    "logPriceDiesel <- log(priceFType$diesel)\n",
    "\n",
    "#Let's split the price vector by Aspiration\n",
    "table(auto.sub$aspiration)\n",
    "priceAspiration <- split(auto.sub$price, as.factor(auto.sub$aspiration), drop = FALSE)\n",
    "\n",
    "#Compute logarithms\n",
    "logPriceTurbo <- log(priceAspiration$turbo)\n",
    "logPriceStandard <- log(priceAspiration$std)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "_cell_guid": "781900d1-d725-441a-95f1-ddb8b8d11abe",
    "_uuid": "db7d97625b40804ea0c23dc88d35f07f5625fdf7"
   },
   "source": [
    "Now we want to test if:\n",
    "1. Price of gas cars is significantly different from that of diesel cars\n",
    "2. Price of turbo aspiration cars are significantly different from that of std aspiration cars\n",
    "\n",
    "For these tests, we shall use the logarithm of prices, since they more or less closer to being normally distributed than just the prices\n",
    "\n",
    "## T-test\n",
    "\n",
    "The difference in means between two Normal distributions with unknown variance follows a Sudent's t-distribution. The t-test is any statistical hypothesis test in which the test statistic follows a Student's t-distribution under the null hypothesis.\n",
    "The Student t-test is one of the oldest and widely used hypothesis test. \n",
    "\n",
    "Let's start with **1. Price of gas cars is significantly different from that of diesel cars**\n",
    "\n",
    "  Null hypothesis: **$H_0$**: The difference in average log(Price) of gas cars & diesel cars is 0 **Vs**\n",
    "\n",
    "  Alternative hypothesis **$H_a$**: The difference in average log(Price) is not equal to 0\n",
    "\n",
    "At 95% confidence. "
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "#Testing if price of diesel cars vary signifcantly from that of gas cars\n",
    "\n",
    "#Plot for comparing means\n",
    "plot.t <- function(a, b, cols = c('title1', 'title2'), nbins = 20)\n",
    "{\n",
    "  maxs <- max(c(max(a), max(b)))\n",
    "  mins <- min(c(min(a), min(b)))\n",
    "  breaks = seq(maxs, mins, length.out = (nbins + 1))\n",
    "  par(mfrow = c(2, 1))\n",
    "  hist(a, breaks = breaks, main = paste('Histogram of', cols[1]), xlab = cols[1])\n",
    "  abline(v = mean(a), lwd = 4, col = 'red') #Put a line at the mean\n",
    "  hist(b, breaks = breaks, main = paste('Histogram of', cols[2]), xlab = cols[2])\n",
    "  abline(v = mean(b), lwd = 4, col = 'red')\n",
    "  par(mfrow = c(1, 1))\n",
    "}\n",
    "\n",
    "options(repr.plot.width=5, repr.plot.height=5) ## Set the plot area.\n",
    "plot.t(logPriceDiesel,logPriceGas, c('logPrice of Diesel cars', 'logPrice of Gas cars'))"
   ]
  },

    "_uuid": "a52908662b11dacdad5d98625e00771120a996d6"
   },
   "source": [
    "The red line in the graph shows where the mean of the logarithm of prices are. From this we can see that there is a small difference in means. Let's do a t-test to see if this is significant enough:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 22,
   "metadata": {
    "_cell_guid": "4b868d48-1f5a-43a9-a627-9c703cf2c95c",
    "_uuid": "937c77136bcab2f3239882af183f2b5dadfae09c"
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "\n",
       "\tWelch Two Sample t-test\n",
       "\n",
       "data:  logPriceDiesel and logPriceGas\n",
       "t = 2.0019, df = 23.942, p-value = 0.05675\n",
       "alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0\n",
       "95 percent confidence interval:\n",
       " -0.007204235  0.470292829\n",
       "sample estimates:\n",
       "mean of x mean of y \n",
       " 9.557420  9.325876 \n"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "t.test(logPriceDiesel,logPriceGas, alternative = \"two.sided\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "_cell_guid": "ecce3395-9b4c-450b-811b-b0833b306961",
    "_uuid": "88bddc6e86aa3671810ac2dadaa6c80f282fffd5"
   },
   "source": [
    "Since p-value is a little over 0.05 and 0 lies in the 95% confidence interval (-0.007204235,  0.470292829), we do not have sufficient evidence to reject the null hypothesis that the prices of diesel cars are not significantly different from that of gas cars\n",
    "\n",
    "Now let's test **2. Price of turbo aspiration cars is significantly different from that of std aspiration cars**\n",
    "\n",
    "Null hypothesis: **$H_0$**: The difference in average log(Price) of turbo aspiration cars and std aspiration cars is 0 **Vs**\n",
    "\n",
    "Alternative hypothesis **$H_a$**: The difference in average log(Price) is not equal to 0\n",
    "\n",
    "At 95% confidence."
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "#Testing if price of turbo cars vary signifcantly from that of standard cars\n",
    "options(repr.plot.width=5, repr.plot.height=5) ## Set the plot area.\n",
    "plot.t(logPriceTurbo,logPriceStandard, c('logPrice of Turbo cars', 'logPrice of Standard cars'))\n",
    "t.test(logPriceTurbo,logPriceStandard, alternative = \"two.sided\")"
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "_cell_guid": "9fee8f1b-fb7c-4514-8517-d90544b698ab",

   },
   "source": [
    "From the graphs, we can see there is some difference between the average prices (the red line marks the average price)\n",
    "\n",
    "Since p-value is significantly less than 0.05 and 0 does not lie in the 95% confidence interval (0.1876238 0.4901126), we  reject the null hypothesis that the prices of turbo cars are not significantly different from that of standard cars. In other words, this test implies that the prices of **turbo cars** are **significantly** different from that of **standard cars**."
   ]
